impoverishment and in continued violence against them. 
</p>
<p>80. The failure to address women&#8217;s ES rights in post-conflict situations, contributes to 
women&#8217;s poverty and material insecurity and thus, their vulnerability to abuse, including 
trafficking.<b>89</b> The invisibility of VAW during and after the conflict/disaster is over exacerbates 
gender inequalities and marginalizes women in reconstruction and State-building processes 
despite Security Council Resolution 1325 (2000) on women, peace and security in which the 
Council recognizes the right of women to participate in these processes.<b>90</b> Research suggests that 
women can be empowered in post-crisis situations<b>91</b> if endemic problems in society are 
addressed and the ES rights of citizens during the rebuilding of societies after crises are ensured 
in a non-discriminatory manner.<b>92</b> 
</p>
